Pre-heat your #oven{} to 220 degrees. Wash the @sweet potato{1} then chop lengthways
into wedges the thickness of your index finger. Toss in @olive oil{2%tbsp} and
@salt{1/4%tsp}, then spread in a single layer on a #baking tray{}. Cook on the top
shelf of your oven until crispy (around ~{25%minutes}).

> Save the garlic salt for your burgers!

In a #bowl{} mix together the @British beef mince{250%g}, the @garlic salt{1/4%tsp},
half the @ketchup{1/2%portion}, the @dried oregano{1%tsp} and a few grinds of
@black pepper{a few grinds}.

Divide the mixture into two equal portions and then gently form into burger patties
roughly 1 1/2cm thick.

> It is important that you press the meat together firmly enough to make it stick,
> yet not so firmly that it becomes densely packed, as this will give a tough texture.

Once your sweet potatoes are almost ready, split the @brioche bun{2} in half. Put a
#frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Toast the brioche buns for ~{2%minutes} on each
side then remove.

> You could use your toaster but whatever happens don't let them burn!

In the same frying pan, heat @olive oil{1%tbsp} on medium-high heat. Once hot, gently
add in your patties and cook for ~{5-6%minutes} on each side, or until the meat is
fully cooked with no pink bits remaining. Whilst you are cooking the second side of
the burger, grate the @smoked cheese{2%slices} on top (of the cooked side!) for the
last ~{1%minute} so that it melts.

Meanwhile, thinly slice the @vine tomatoes{2}.

Toss the @wild rocket{1%handful} in a little drizzle of @olive oil{a little} with a
small pinch of @salt{small pinch} and @pepper{small pinch}.

Spread a little of the remaining ketchup on your toasted brioche buns. Place your
burger on top, then lay your tomato slices and rocket on top and serve with your
sweet potato wedges on the side.

> You can serve any remaining tomatoes and rocket on the side too.